nkrijk"},"en":{"about 1170–Abt 1240":"about 1170–about 1240","1170–1240":"1170–1240","1172–1243":"1172–1243","1160–Male":"1160–Deceased","1119–Male":"1119–Deceased","1210–1270":"1210–1270","1210–Male":"1210–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1150–Male":"1150–Deceased","Abt 1240":"about 1240","about 1170":"about 1170","1210":"1210","1243":"1243","1240":"1240","1150":"1150","1172":"1172","1270":"1270","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1119":"1119","Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom","Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Maelor Gymraeg, Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Llewellyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>Llywelyn</i>, derived from British Celtic <i>Lugubelinos</i>, itself from the divine name <i>Lugus</i> + an uncertain second element often used alone as a name. Through association with <i>llew</i> ‘lion’, it was altered to <i>Llewelyn</i>. This was the name of two princes of north Wales who held the Normans at bay for many years in the 13th century. Etymologically speaking, the form with a fourth <i>-l-</i> is an error, not found as an original Welsh name, but this is now much the most common spelling in the US."],"variants":[{"name":"Lewelling","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Llewellyn  ."]},{"name":"Lewellen","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Llewellyn  ."]},{"name":"Lewallen","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Llewellyn  ."]},{"name":"Louallen","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh <b>Llewelyn</b> (see   Llewellyn  )."]},{"name":"Luellen","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Llewellyn  ."]},{"name":"Welling","meanings":["English: habitational name from Welwyn (Hertfordshire) or Welling in Bexley (Kent), with a suspicion of an alternative unidentified source. The Hertfordshire placename means ‘at the willow trees’, from Old English <i>wel(i)gum</i>, dative plural form of <i>welig</i> ‘willow’. The Kent placename may derive from Old English <i>wella</i> ‘well, spring, stream’ + the placename forming suffix <i>-ing</i>. In some cases this name may represent a development of   Llewellyn  , particularly near the Welsh border.","German: habitational name from any of various places in the Rhineland called Welling or Wellingen."]},{"name":"Luallen","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Llewellyn  ."]},{"name":"Lewellyn","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Llewellyn  ."]},{"name":"Llewelyn","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Llewellyn  ."]}]},{"name":"Angharad","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Old Celtic intensive prefix <i>an-</i> + <i>cār</i> ‘love’ + the noun suffix <i>-ad</i>. This was the name of the mother of the 12th-century chronicler  Giraldus Cambrensis  (‘Gerald the Welshman’). In the <i>Mabinogi</i>, Angharad Golden Hand at first rejects Peredur's suit, but later falls in love with him when he comes back as the unknown Mute Knight. The name has been strongly revived in Wales since the 1940s, borne, for example, by the actress  Angharad Rees  (  1949-2012 )."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Verch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Orlo.","German: variant of   Ferch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferch","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Angharad Verch Llewellyn was born about 1170, in Wales, United Kingdom as the daughter of Llywelyn Ap Meurig Caradog. She had at least 2 sons with Iorwerth ap Griffi ap Ieuaf. She was buried in Glamorgan, Wales, U